                <h1 class="h1-display pt-xs-2 mt-xs-2 bt-xs-1 mb-xs-2">Podcast Transcript: How to Help Buyers Find Your Items With Attributes</h1>

                <p class="h4-display text-larger excerpt text-gray mb-xs-3">Get tips from an Etsy expert on how to add accurate attributes to your listings so your items reach the right shoppers.</p>

               
            </hgroup>

                                <ul id="share" data-track-scroll="seller-handbook-share-links" class="share-links list-inline mb-xs-4">
    
    

                


    </ul>

            
            <article class="prose prose-article pb-xs-4 pb-md-6">
                <figure><img alt="Attributes podcast transcript" src="https://i.etsystatic.com/inv/48db73/2003220492/inv_fullxfull.2003220492_kvrnf4d1.jpg?version=0" title="Attributes podcast transcript"></figure><p><strong><em>The following is a transcript of a podcast episode released in September 2019. The transcript has been edited slightly for this format.</em> <em>You can listen to the episode on <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/etsy-success-podcast/id1239556187">Apple Podcasts</a>, <a href="https://soundcloud.com/etsy-699847215">SoundCloud</a>,</em> <a href="https://open.spotify.com/show/0ffVPNqsRp3c2yy0mBcgp6?si=W582v_UcQP6lloKiRDaNhg"><em>Spotify</em></a> <em>or wherever you get your podcasts.</em></strong></p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Jenny Benevento is returning to the show to talk about how attributes can help you connect with the right buyers. She’s the senior manager of the Taxonomy team at Etsy. She and her team used search data, buyer interviews, merchandise research, and analytics to discover what shoppers want to know about items on Etsy. With that information, they create attributes, which are one of the most important factors in helping items appear in relevant searches. Welcome back to the show, Jenny! Thanks for being here.</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Thanks for having me back.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: First, can you give our listeners a refresher on what you do at Etsy?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: I manage a team of people who research what buyers need to know to find and purchase items. Then we create attributes for sellers to fill that information out in a controlled way so that we can give buyers that information.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Can you tell me, in your own words, what attributes are?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Attributes are the fields we ask you to fill out after you’ve answered what category your item belongs in. They tend to be specific to the category that you’re in. They could be size, style, colour, yes or no questions, measurements.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Got it. You’re kind of like a liaison between buyers and sellers in a way. You take the research about buyers, and then use that to inform how sellers will fill out their listings, which then makes the listings more findable by the buyers looking for those items.</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Exactly.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: I’ve heard that attributes can play a pretty big role in helping buyers find your items. Can you speak a little bit to that?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Sure. They’re like free super tags. They’re extra keywords that you can add on top of those 13&nbsp;tags that you have, and they’re used in search. If they truly and accurately apply to your item, there’s no reason not to add them. Once sellers fill out an attribute enough, then we can also show it to buyers as a filter on searches and in the category that they’re in.</p>
<p>If you want to appear in buyer’s filtered searches you should add attributes, but only if they truly apply to your listing. Most importantly, by collecting this information in the specific, controlled way that we do, we can internally reuse this information and make you more visible to buyers in the ways that they want to see items. We can also build cool, new features for buyers that your items will be included in.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Exciting. That’s great because there are so many ways to describe an item on Etsy. This really broadens seller’s possibilities for getting found. OK, so like I was saying before, attributes are what sellers fill out when they’re creating a listing, which then inform what filters are available to shoppers when they browse or search. So what about shoppers? What do you know about how they’ve been engaging with these filters?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: We know that shoppers who interact with these filters tend to buy more expensive items. We also know that buyers don’t like using filters with low coverage. By low coverage, I mean a filter that returns very few results. If we have 100,000 items in the search results and a buyer uses a filter, and that filter causes the results to return just 20 items, that makes it seem broken. The buyer no longer trusts the results.</p>
<p>If only 20% of sellers fill out an attribute, showing a filter based on that attribute to buyers isn’t going to be helpful because such a drastic reduction in results makes them lose confidence in those search results. We have to wait until a large number of sellers fill out that data to show it to buyers as a filter. When we do, sellers who have filled out that attribute show in those filtered search results. Sellers who haven’t, don’t.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Yeah, I know I use filters to narrow my search all the time because there are just so many amazing items on Etsy. What are some best practices when it comes to using attributes?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: First, if you don’t see any attributes in your category, don’t worry. The first few we add to a category are things like colour, occasion, celebration, size and material. We’re trying to roll them out in areas with the largest number of items. Once you start seeing them, fill them out truthfully and accurately. If you enter incorrect responses, a buyer will be unhappy and not buy your item. It’s disappointing to them, especially for new Etsy buyers. Putting misleading information in your attributes and listings makes Etsy feel untrustworthy. It’s just a bad experience for the buyer.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Yeah, because if they use the filter and it shows them an item totally unrelated to that filter, that’s just frustrating. How do you do it correctly?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Say your item is red. Choose red. If your item is cherry, scarlet or crimson, we’d love if you still chose red and then also mention that special colour name in the item description. Likewise, if your sweater has a sparkly Christmas tree on it, it would likely get Christmas as the celebration. But say you have a really cool gold band. It could be a gift for someone for a bunch of different celebrations. Feel free to mention that in your description, but don’t fill out Christmas as the celebration. Imagine if you went to a Christmas section and nothing had Christmas theming. That’s what happens when you categorise things that aren’t specifically for that celebration using an attribute for it.</p>
<p>It not only drives buyers not to buy your item, but also not to buy from Etsy in general. If you’re frequently changing the response to an attribute, it’s not the best use of your time. Think about whether an item is themed for the celebration, not good as a gift for it. I’d also think from the buyer's point of view. Would a buyer be happy with your item being a result if they used this attribute response as a filter?</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Right, like if I was searching “Christmas sweater”, I’m probably looking for a sweater that has, say, Santa or a Christmas tree on it. I wouldn’t want to see just any sweater that could potentially be given as a Christmas gift. Let’s say you have a handmade ring. How would a seller go about adding attributes for that? Can you break it down for me step-by-step?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Sure! OK, say you’re listing an engagement ring. You made it of 24 karat gold and it has a solitaire diamond in it. You tell us it’s handmade in the listing form. Then you type “engagement ring” in the category box. You’ll assign it to the Engagement Rings category. From that, you can see it’ll show up for buyers in the Engagement Rings categories in Weddings and the Engagement Rings category in Jewellery automatically. When you select a category, you get attributes specific to that category. We have over 200,000 rings. People are very particular about what they want in them for obvious reasons. That’s just too many to browse. So we’ve added a lot of attributes here.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: That makes sense. There’s definitely a lot of incredible jewellery on Etsy.</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: From there, you can choose a recipient. We’ve added this in lots of places, but we ask it here to determine if the ring is traditionally gendered. For example, is this style a women’s, men’s or gender-neutral ring? In this case, we’d say women’s. </p>
<p>Then we let you choose up to five materials in Engagement Rings. We’re in the process of allowing you to add different numbers of materials on different items, but we also don’t want people to pick every possible option. Only choose the ones that actually represent your item. We’ve heard from sellers who have been under the impression that picking all options shows them to more people and will get their item sold faster. But in fact, we see when buyers find results that don’t match what they’re looking for, they’re less likely to trust that seller, less likely to buy that item, and less likely to even buy from Etsy. Really it’s best to choose only things that accurately reflect your item. You may have three materials or 27. I’d choose the ones you know buyers are most interested in. In this example, our ring is gold. I’d only select gold.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: I know that a lot of people who wear jewellery tend to only wear gold or silver, so it would make sense that they’d start their searches with that material.</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: We then ask you if your ring is recycled. If you used recycled pieces in this item, say yes. In my case, I’d say no. </p>
<p>Now we come to gemstone. In my case, I have one diamond. I would choose that. You can choose to vary on stone here. If you have more than one stone, I’d choose the largest one. Or if your gemstone isn’t listed, I would skip this. In all cases, I would also write all of the gem names in the description. We get a lot of comments from sellers to make this list longer. We do plan to do this in the future. We love all gemstones, but these are the ones we see buyers searching for the most. </p>
<p>Next you can tell us if your stone is raw or not. I’d say no here. Then you can tell us the colour of the band and the colour of the gem, and that’s gold and colourless in my example. We’ve seen buyers usually know what colour stone they want, but not the name. Some gemstones come in more than one colour. This really helps people who know the colour they want and not the gem names. </p>
<p>Next up, you can pick a size scale depending on what country you’re in. When we ask for a size in these dropdowns, we automatically translate it to the size it is in the other scales. If you give us the French size, when buyers use a filter for the equivalent size in the US, your item comes up in search results automatically. This is really one of the best reasons to use this type of structured data instead of just the open text in your item description, because we’re doing that work for you. I’m going to say this is a US 9. You can also tell us here if it’s adjustable. I’ll say no.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: That’s so helpful. I can hardly remember my ring sizes in US sizes, let alone what they’d be in countries all over the world.</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Next in Engagement Rings, you can choose a style. Again, we’ve begun with a limited list of styles because we’ve seen sellers add a bunch of different styles to their titles, tags, and descriptions that are contradictory and misleading to buyers. We allow one style choice and chose styles that we see buyers looking for the most, but also ones that most people could consistent identify. In this case, I’d say my ring is a minimalist style. If one of these styles doesn’t capture your item, skip it and add your style in the description.</p>
<p>Now there are some “yes or no” questions left. Can you personalise this ring? That is, if a buyer wants their name engraved or to choose a different stone, can they? Is it a spinner ring? I’d say no to both of these. </p>
<p>Finally, we’ve pre-filled out the occasion of Engagement for you. Engagement rings are fairly expensive and meant to last a lifetime. They have a lot of attributes. Hopefully this example helps you decide whether you should fill something out or not in your section.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Thank you for going into such a detailed example for us, Jenny. You covered so much great information. Is there anything else sellers should know about attributes?</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: My pleasure. Etsy was able to grow our business and sellers’ businesses together because of the amazing and unique products sellers make and find. In fact, Etsy now offers over 60 million items for buyers to browse. As you can imagine, sifting through all of those listings can be daunting. Think of attributes as guides to help buyers find just the right thing.</p>
<p>Lots of these buyers don’t know the specific words artists use to describe all the amazing details for their items because they’re not experts. Buyers now expect help when they browse and search on Etsy because they get that help on other e-commerce websites. They may hate the colour brown or be allergic to wool. They might have an uncommonly sized foot or feel that only certain clothing styles help express who they are.</p>
<p>When we ask you to fill out attributes, we’re asking for information that might seem simplistic to you. It might not have every possible option. We know that. This is the foundation we’re building for buyers. Every year we continue building out more options. We’ve started with ones we’ve seen make the most difference to buyers based on the analytics we collect on their shopping and searching habits.</p>
<p>Only 51% of categories on Etsy have at least one category-specific attribute you can add to your listings. Only 54% of categories on Etsy have search filters shoppers can use that are powered by attributes. The more accurate data we get from sellers, the more we can build more options for you and features for buyers.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: That’s so exciting. It does seem like it would take a bit more time on Etsy since it’s a marketplace with so many unique artists and sellers, and not a retail corporation.</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Yes, most e-commerce sites automatically get this information from the manufacturer for their mass-produced items. This makes it easier to quickly create filters and descriptions for them. We don’t have that ability because everything our sellers make is so unique. We started with a limited set of options which we’re asking you to fill out truthfully and accurately.</p>
<p>Once those are filled out, we’ll add more and build great user experiences for buyers on top of that. But we can’t do that without your data. We hear your voices. “Why isn’t my very specific material or colour or size available?” We’ll get there. In the meantime, we have to cover the most widespread needs that will help the most buyers and sellers along the way.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Now it’s time for our lightning round where we collected questions from sellers in the forums for you to answer. </p>
<p>Our first question comes from Beeble Weezy who says, “Many attribute categories are lacking in basic choices to accurately describe our items. I’d like to know if there are any plans in the future for more attributes to be added to our choices. For example, my vintage jewellery is mostly gold-filled. There’s no option for gold-filled or gold-plated in materials. I’m reluctant to choose gold as I feel that should only be used for solid gold. Any plans for those lists to expand?”</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: Yes! This is my dream too. We’re trying to cover the most basic options first. Once we get good coverage there, we’ll move on to more specific cases. I love that especially our jewellery sellers are concerned about this as an important distinction because they’re craftspeople. Many jewellery buyers don’t have your experience and don’t know the huge difference between these things, though. If they do, they still want to narrow by gold and then get into more specifics. So don’t feel like an item has to be 100% gold to indicate gold. I’d also indicate the metal it’s filled with as a material too. Think about it as, “Would an average person be happy with this result if they narrowed by this material in a filter?” I’d definitely still indicate that it isn’t solid gold in your description. We already have a place to add your write-in option: in your descriptions and tags which are also used in search and by buyers making a final decision.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Art by Jocelyn says, “When it comes to celebration and occasion attributes, do we choose one that would designate what our item could be gifted as? Or are we to choose this if our item actually is in that theme design-wise? How do we interpret whether we should assign that attribute to a listing?”</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: If a celecration or occasion doesn’t relate to your item, feel free to ignore it. It would apply if it was a theme of the item. For example, a Christmas tree is for the celebration of Christmas, not a gift you give someone for Christmas. In our next release, we’ll add helper text around these attributes to make this more clear.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Strangeways Vintage says, “The attributes for clothing, especially vintage, are woefully inadequate. Is it possible for someone with a deeper knowledge of fashion to revise our options? We need some basic ones like ‘dropwaist’ and ‘strapless’ as well as many more style options. ‘Novelty’ as a print option would be huge for vintage clothes”.</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: We know our attributes don’t have every possible answer anyone could ever think of and there are several reasons for this. First, if we included every possible answer, it would be very difficult for sellers and buyers to use such a long list. We try to prune the list for answers most searched for by buyers. These are just the beginning.</p>
<p>We’ll eventually build more, the more these are used. Also many buyers don’t have a deep knowledge of fashion. Something that might make sense to a professional sewer or vintage seller isn’t always a term or detail that a buyer looks for. If there’s information you don’t feel is captured by the structured data, we always encourage you to include it in the descriptions or tags for buyers who do have a deep knowledge of clothing construction.</p>
<p>Finally, we try to pick attribute values that are clear to everyone. A novelty print to you might not be a novelty print to someone else. We’d much rather you tell us specifically if it’s a swirl pattern, for example. Again, we encourage you to add novelty in the description for buyers who do want to search that way.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: The Old Barn Door asks, “Could we please have the ability to add our own attributes such as Friendship, Thinking of You, Good Luck, New Baby, etcetera? Often the available options do not apply. While putting it in the tags helps, it would certainly boost many items to have the appropriate occasion or celebration.”</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: The point of attributes is to have a standard set of tags so that we can show these to buyers in filters. You’re very welcome to add this info elsewhere in your listing, which will still be picked up in search. If we allowed free text for these attributes, we wouldn’t be able to use it for filters and upcoming features. The fastest way toward us expanding those lists is for sellers to use the current attributes correctly.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Seaside Rose Creations asks, “How many buyers do they interview to gather their research? How often do they conduct these interviews? What is the criteria for utilising the information from specific buyers? How does this team know this is what the majority of shoppers want?”</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: User research involves qualitative interviews where we discuss features of the site one-on-one with hundreds of individual buyers and sellers, and quantitative research where we survey thousands of people annually. We have an entire department at Etsy that does this research every day. We use their findings to make decisions.</p>
<p>We also use analytics of all the buyers searching and browsing on Etsy, and all the listings all sellers fill out. When there’s an overwhelming trend in these kinds of data, we tend to take that into consideration. For example, if we see a lot of searches for something with a size or a material type as a modifier&nbsp;— like wool dress, size 12&nbsp;— it’s a good sign an attribute and filter for size and material would be good in that category.</p>
<p>We then do research on the possible sizes and materials the dresses are made in and what people search for when they’re looking for those types of dresses. Then we show potential attributes and filters to sellers and buyers in this category to discuss if it works before releasing it. We always have to balance the most complete possible set of responses with usability for sellers and buyers. Putting it in front of people one-on-one is usually the best way for us to do that.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Glamories says, “Please become more international when it comes to measurements, clothes and shoe sizes. Big parts of the world use the metric system. The dimensions we put in should be automatically converted to inches or vice versa. The same goes for clothes and shoe sizes.”</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: I couldn’t agree more. Converting measurements is one of the hardest things about an international marketplace. I have great news for you. We already do this in a lot of places, almost 1,000 categories, especially in craft supplies, clothing and shoes. </p>
<p>Whenever we ask you to choose a scale, that means we’re translating sizes for you. When I ask you for a scale that could mean an open measurement where there’s a blank and you choose an imperial or metric measurement like inches or centimetres. It could mean a size scale like in dresses where you choose US letter, US numerical, French, German, Japanese, Australia and UK sizes. If you tell us a dress is a French size 42, we show American customers who see that listing the US size equivalent. It’s also shown when buyers filter by that American size. In addition to the filter, we show the size on the listing page in the local size. Of course, there are always more categories and more countries we can do this in. We’re far ahead of competitors in this respect. The more we see sellers filling this out, the more we’ll expand this feature.</p>
<p><strong>Tess</strong>: Yesterday Gets Better asks, “Please add ‘multi’ under colour attributes. You have 'rainbow.' Very few multicoloured items are rainbow-coloured whereas all rainbow-coloured items are multicoloured.”</p>
<p><strong>Jenny</strong>: When we ask you about colour, we want to know what colour an item actually is. Is it red and blue? Multicolour doesn’t tell us that. As a person who wears many multicoloured things, I do want things that are pink, blue and yellow but I never want things that are brown, beige and white. If you tell us what actual colours things are, we can allow buyers to get more specific. In the future, we do plan to extend the number of colours you can apply to your item. For now, enter the two most prevalent. </p>
<p>I’m glad you mentioned rainbow. It’s one of my favourites and feels very Etsy to us. Use this for things that are actually rainbow-coloured. For example, red, orange, yellow, green, blue, etcetera. We added this because buyers look for it a lot, and we have a ton of rainbow-coloured and themed merchandise. It’s also great for pride searches. If you think about a buyer narrowing by rainbow and finding your item, would they be excited or confused? That should be your answer on whether to choose it, or any other colour.</p>
<p><em>Learn more about attributes in <a href="https://www.etsy.com/in-en/seller-handbook/article/604203126614">our new chapter</a> of the Ultimate Guide to Etsy Search.</em></p>
